			<div type="commentary">
				<p>&lt;viṃṁkhno&gt; may represent the Sanskrit name
					Viṣṇu complementing &lt;jatra&gt; in the next line
					which may be from Candrā. However, &lt;khno&gt; could also be the same word as &lt;knoṄ&gt; in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00001">1</ref>, l. 1, or even &lt;kno&gt; in &lt;kno&gt; in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00020">20</ref>,
					l. 3, if the aspiration of &lt;k&gt; is not phonemic (as in Khmer in which /kn/ is phonetically [kʰn]).</p>
				<!-- MM2AG: why did you think jatra could be from feminine candrā rather than masculine candraḥ? BTW, I originally thought khno in 017 was the same word as khnoṅ· in 001, as I couldn't imagine why Viṣṇu would be borrowed with -kh- instead of -s- since Pyu does have sn- as in sniḥ 'year'. Just checked and found Pyu snuḥ in 006 and 020. Is there any Middle Indic form like vikhṇu < vikṣṇu? Turner's dictionary lists the unspecified Prakrit forms viṇhu and veṇhu. -->
				<!-- AG2MM: pronunciation of written <ṣ> as /kh/ is common in certain parts of India (see e.g. <http://dsal.uchicago.edu/dictionaries/turner/frontmatter/introduction.html>). This presumably also reflects some historical developments in the local NIA languages, but I don't know the linguistic facts. jatra presumably represent Candrā because the person is indicated to be a queen (mahādevī). -->
				<p>&lt;ṅiṁ kda&gt; appears to match &lt;ṅiTṁ kdaṄ&gt; in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00016">16</ref>,
					PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00020">20</ref>, PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00027">27</ref> and PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00032">32</ref></p>
			</div>
			<div type="bibliography">
				<!--ASI 1929-30, 152, 182. — PPPB I, 66, 75 n. 28, 149. — PR, 22.-->
				<!--[Todo: markup citedRange elements if necessary]-->
				<p>First reported in <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASI"/><citedRange>1929-30: 152, 182</citedRange></bibl>, where it was reported found near 001, with 8 lines of Pyu. <bibl><ptr target="bib:ThaMyat1963_01"/><citedRange>22</citedRange></bibl> is an eye drawing and transliteration based on the ASI photograph. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Luce1985_01"/><citedRange>I, 66, 75 n. 28, 149</citedRange></bibl>, provides an overview of earlier work and notes the name of a queen, &lt;mahadevi sri jatra&gt;, in lines 3-4. <bibl><ptr target="bib:SeinWin2016_01"/><citedRange>18-21</citedRange></bibl> gives eye drawings, a new reading and a glossary. Re-edited here from published photographs and from our team’s RTIs.</p>
